-- South African Stocks Climb For a Third Day, Led Up by BHP, Mondi, Netcare
-- B y   M i k e   C o h e n   a n d   G a r t h   T h e u n i s s e n
-- 2010-11-01T11:10:29Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-01/equities-in-south-africa-rally-for-third-day-anglo-platinum-mondi-move.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose for a third day, climbing 20.09, or 0.1
percent, to 30,450.99 at 1:06 p.m. in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ) fell for the fourth time in
five days, dropping 3.78 rand, or 0.6 percent, to 689.22 rand.
The world’s largest platinum producer said it has ended talks
announced on Oct. 29. Anglo Platinum gained the most in almost
two months in the previous day of trading after saying it was in
talks that may have a “material effect” on its shares.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, rose 2.92 rand, or 1.2 percent, to 249.60 rand. Copper
gained as much as 1.7 percent to $8,340.75 a metric ton on the
London Metal Exchange after manufacturing accelerated in China,
the world’s largest user of industrial metals.  Mondi Ltd.  (MND SJ) climbed for a second day, advancing 39
cents, or 0.7 percent, to 58.59 rand. Europe’s largest maker of
office paper said underlying operating profit in the three
months through September was higher than in each of the prior
two quarters and “well in excess” of the same period a year
earlier.  Netcare Ltd.  (NTC SJ) rose 53 cents, or 3.6 percent, to
15.10 rand, a second day of gains. South Africa’s largest
private-hospital operator said earnings per share excluding one-
time items for the year through September are expected to be
from 20 percent to 30 percent higher than in the previous year.  To contact the reporters on this story:
